<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-03T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-03T11:00:00-05:00" n="33" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d33">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72114/3267</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Denmark</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GSU1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grant-Smith</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-03T17:00:00+01:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 3, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 4, 6.50
                                p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1906. Department’s unnumbered [<hi rend="italic">668</hi>], January
                                8.<note n="1" xml:id="d33fn1">See footnote 1, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_18">p. 18</ref>.</note> Danish
                            Government agrees to the free transmission through Denmark of postal
                            matter destined for prisoners of war. Text follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>Monsieur le Chargé d’Affaires: Referring to the note of January
                                    9, 1918, No. 773, I have honor to communicate that pursuant to
                                    transport rules laid down in the Hague regulations of 1907,
                                    article 16, and in the universal postal convention of 1906,
                                    article 2 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>], section 4, and in
                                    accordance with point of view taken by the Royal Danish
                                    Government in equal matters, all letters, money orders and
                                    objects of value as well as parcels destined for or in camps of
                                    prisoners or camps of concentration will be transmitted postage
                                    free <pb facs="0106" n="22" xml:id="pg_22"/> to their
                                    destination. I avail myself of this opportunity to renew to you,
                                    Monsieur le Chargé d’Affaires, the assurance of my high
                                    consideration. Signed <persName corresp="#p_SE1">Erik
                                        Scavenius</persName>.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>